steve-b@access.digex.net (Steve Brinich) writes:
>  Another groundless assumption.  First, to draw favorable conclusions about
>Clipper based on selected technical information released by its creators is
>obviously unwise; it is rather like evaluating a computer system based solely
>on the information found in its advertising campaign.  Second, there is no
>available basis on which to rule out other explanations for the extra
>complexity (e.g. concealment of a trapdoor).

Another way of looking at it: NSA claims that the design of the
Clipper chip is "protected" as a secret.  Is this not "security
through obscurity"?  Does this mean that if you know how the chip
works you can crack it?

